load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

  • Generalizability: The dataset comprises of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before the year 2016. This suggests that the data (movies) are generalizable to a wider base of all movies. However, they may only be generalized to movies produced and released before 2016, and only to the extent of which movies are selected to be included on IMDb and Rotten Tomatoes in the first place. In other words, if there are restrictions at the very start on certain types of movie inclusion, such as movies limited to specific languages, then the generalizability of these 651 randomly sampled movies will be undermined.

  • Causality: Since the collected data are observational in nature and not yielded by random assignment, causality may not be inferred from the results.

Part 2: Research question

Do movie ratings on IMDb differ according to their genre, runtime and critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes?

I am interested to learn if there are certain movie genres that render more popularity amongst people, and whether or not movie runtimes also influence a movie’s popularity. However, it is to note that because I am using movie rating on IMDb as proxy to a movie’s popularity, I am assuming that a movie’s popularity is reflected by its ratings given on IMDb, as opposed to say, the number of times the movie was watched. This assumption may be inaccurate.

I am also keen to learn if there is a relationship between movie ratings on IMDb and critics ratings on Rotten Tomatoes - both of which are online databases of aggregated information on many movies. If the relationship between movie ratings on IMDb and critics ratings of movies on Rotten Tomatoes are inversely proportional, then it provides an additional validation of a movie’s popularity.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

The variables that I will be using are:

  • Response variable: imdb_rating (movie rating on IMDb reflecting a movie’s popularity)

  • Explanatory variables/ predictors: genre (movie genre: action, comedy, documentary etc), runtime (runtime of movie in minutes), critics_rating (critics rating grouped on Rotten Tomatoes: Certified Fresh, Fresh, Rotten)

I will now create a new dataframe and only selecting my interested variables.

It is also to be noted that most of the individual boxplots overlap with each other. This implies that there may not be significant differences in averages between the different movie genres. An inference test may be conducted to validate this statement.

Part 4: Modeling

Now I’d like build a multiple linear regression model consisting of three of my explanatory variables of interest.

#fit model
lm1<-lm(imdb_rating~genre+runtime+critics_rating,data=movies1)

summary(lm1)

Interpretation of regression output/ t-test

Looking at the estimates on the regression output, the linear model can be written as follows:

movie rating on IMDb = 5.98 - 0.16 genre: animation + 0.4 genre: art house - 0.17 genre: comedy + 1.04 genre: documentary + 0.27 genre: drama - 0.12 genre: horror + 0.69 genre: musicals + 0.22 genre: mystery + 0.14 genre: other - 0.5 genre: scifi + 0.01 runtime - 0.42 critics rating: fresh - 1.35 critics rating: rotten

Intercept coefficient: The intercept is 5.98, meaning when all of the variables are valued at 0, the movie rating on IMDb will be 5.98 - this is not meaningful in any practical way.

Estimate coefficients: A one unit increase in the respective explanatory variable yields an increase or decrease of movie rating on IMDb by its corresponding estimate - with all other variables held constant. For example, a movie with a critics rating of Rotten on Rotten Tomatoes will have a decrease in its movine rating on IMDb by 1.34.

Individual P-value coefficients: There are 6 explanatory variables that are significant (p<0.05). This means that slope coefficients for these 6 variables are statistically diferrent from 0 (I reject the null hypothesis claiming that these slope coefficients are 0 aka there is no relationship between the respective explanatory and response variable). In other words, these six variables contribute to the model, while the rest do not.

Multiple R-squared: 51.17% of the total variability of the response variable is explained by the model. Seems like a rather weak fitting model?

F-statistic and overall p-value: The overall p-value for the F-statistic is statistically significant, implying that the model is useful - the model accounts for the variability of the response variable more than it would be expected by chance.

Model selection: Backward elimination using the p-value and adjusted R-squared approaches

Next, I’d like to refine the current model that I have, and evaluate which predictor variables are most useful to the model. Since I will be using the backward elimination strategy, I will start with the full model and drop one predictor at a time until a parsimonious model is obtained.

p-value approach

Key: Repeat the dropping of predictor variables with the highest p-value and refitting of smaller models until all left in the model are significant.

I cannot drop any more variables, as all of my predictor variables have at least one level in which it is significant (p-value<0.05)

Adjusted R-squared approach

Key: Repeat the dropping of predictor variables until the adjusted R-squared cannot be increased further.

  1. Full model

Adjusted R-squared: 0.5017

  1. Drop variable movie genre

Adjusted R-squared: 0.436

  1. Drop variable movie runtime

Adjusted R-squared: 0.474

  1. Drop variable critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes

Adjusted R-squared: 0.2643

Interpretation

Since all of the adjusted R-squared values upon the initial step of dropping each predictor variable are lower than the original full models’ (0.5017), I retain the full model as the best model (at least in comparison).

Diagnostic plots

Four assumptions have to be met for the fitting of the above multiple linear regression model to be valid:

  • Nearly normal residuals around 0
  • Linear relationships between numerical predictor variables and the response variable
  • Constant variability of residuals
  • Independence of residuals

Nearly normal residuals

#plot histogram of residuals 
ggplot(lm1,aes(x=.resid))+geom_histogram(binwidth=0.5)+labs(title="Figure 7: Distribution of residuals")+theme(plot.title=element_text(size=10))+xlab("Residuals")

#plot normal probability plot of residuals 
qqnorm(lm1$residuals,main="Figure 8: Normal probability plot of residuals")
qqline(lm1$residuals)

Interpretation

Figure 7 show a slightly left skewed distribution of residuals. However, Figure 8 does not show any major irregularities or deviations of the residuals except for at the tail ends. This condition seems to be fairy satisfied.

Linear relationship between movie runtime (numerical predictor variable) and movie rating on IMDb

#plot scatterplot of residuals against the numerical predictor variable 
plot(lm1$residuals~movies1$runtime)+title(main="Figure 9: Scatterplot of residuals against movie runtime")

## integer(0)

Interpretation

Figure 9 does not seem to show a randomly scattered plot of residuals around the y-intercept 0. There seems to be an underlying structure of a fan-shaped pattern. This condition does not seem to be satisfied.

Constant variability of residuals

#plot scatterplot of residuals against fitted values
ggplot(lm1,aes(x=.fitted,y=.resid))+geom_point()+labs(title="Figure 10: Scatterplot of residuals vs fitted")+theme(plot.title=element_text(size=10))+xlab("Fitted values")+ylab("Residuals")+geom_hline(yintercept=0,linetype="dashed")

Interpretation

The distribution of residuals on Figure 10 seems to show a fan-shaped pattern - variability of residuals does not seem to be constant across the fitted values.

Independence of residuals

There is no reason to believe that the movies are dependent upon one another.

Part 5: Prediction

I will now use my model to predict the rating of a movie, which is not part of the original sample, on IMDb. The movie is It: Chapter Two released in 2019.

#create new df for movie it
IT<-data.frame(genre="Horror",runtime=169,critics_rating="Rotten")

#predict 
predict(lm1,IT,interval="prediction",level=0.95)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 6.213631 4.656207 7.771055

Interpretation

The model predicts, with a 95% confidence level, that the horror movie It: Chapter Two (2019) that runs for 169 minutes and has a critics rating of Rotten on Rotten Tomatoes, has an average rating between 4.7 and 7.8 on IMDb.

Part 6: Conclusion

Going back to my research question of ‘Do movie ratings on IMDb differ according to the movie’s genre, runtime and critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes?’ - the EDA does not allow me to answer the research question. If anything, it only lets me speculate whether or not movie ratings on IMDb are dependent on a movie’s genre, runtime and critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes - one explanatory variable at a time. To truly deduce if these explanatory variables do make a difference on IMDb ratings, inference tests (hypothesis testing) would have to be conducted - again, one explanatory variable at a time.

As such, a multiple regression analysis serves to describe the relationship between a set of explanatory variables and the response variable. From my multiple regression model, I understand that the genre, runtime and critic’s rating of a movie on Rotten Tomatoes are all significant predictors of a movie’s rating on IMDb. However, movie ratings of only Documentaries, Dramas, or Musicals can be significantly predicted.

Furthermore, it also looks like my model is not a strong model, as the multiple R-squared is only of a mediocre (0.5) value.
